review_blob:
Bottle 750ml. Those have always a great presentation :) Pours with light amber, yellowish colour. White, not big but persistent, small bubbled head. Nose: descendants of saaz type hops, bready, pilsener malt scent. Mouthfeel: average carbonation. Taste: bready, malty, medium sweet, really slightly acidic. Obvious presence of high level of alcohol, but mildly covered by sweetnes and bitternes in aftertaste.
Beware! Its not a session beer, almost 9% abv!! :) Good for fiestas, goes excellently with proper meat portions :) Really good example of regional bire de flamande/garde. Brasserie de Saint Sylvestre, merci beaucoup!!

This comes from one not in love in that style.
Best Pilsner ever. This is truly Bohemian Preciousssss. Sevre model. Constant quality by ages!
All the other bastardized eurolagers can suck his %@&#

500 ml bottle @ home. It?s Slovakian take on Sevre model of Pilseners - the Urquell. I still remember those beers back then, when its brewers were living in one country. Present Bazant is more like his own shadow from the old glory days. Thanks to "red star" brewing corporation - probably. It?s on the malty, sweet side, moderate to light body. Weak hops in aroma and taste - that?s the problem. Slight, shy bitterness in aftertaste - not enough imho. But still, it?s quite drinkable, not bad at all, decent session beer. Better than average eurolager - thats for sure:)

Bottle 550 ml @home. A:pour with black, non opaque color. Beige fluffy, and nicely lacing head.A: woow, after opening, quite strange, not typical roasted stoutish aroma at all! Smells like sort of cocoa liquor extract (ingredient actually). Plus some vanilla  to it. M&T;: Moderate body with shy carbonation. Up front, overwhelming sweet cocoa extract is hiding absolutely everything beside it. Hint of bitterness in aftertaste. O: Sadly, not balanced at all. Quite unusual and over the top ingredient dominates too much. Not session beer, that is!! And even quite hard to finish. Not my pair of boots!

Bottle 335ml @ home. 
Whoa, its one of my fav beer styles. Full appretiation on the warmer side only! Dont drink it when its cold!!!
App: pitch black/very dark brown with very nice, beige, small bubbled & low reducing but lasting head. Aroma: upftont typical english yeast, all of dark malts, hint of plumes or other dark fruits, maybe alc too. Mf&taste;: mild carbonation, very solid sweetish-malty backbone, followed by roasty,  coffie&bitter; sweet chocolate. Silky, smooth aftertaste with hop bitterness and slight warming - without excessive sensation. Alcohol very well hidden :) Overall: excellent o/m stout! Could be even session beer, but beware of almost 6% abv :)
beer_name: Anderson Valley Barney Flats Oatmeal Stout
